The word socialism is derived from 'society'.

Society

1. an organized group of persons associated together for religious,
benevolent, cultural, scientific, political, patriotic, or other purposes.

2. a body of individuals living as members of a community; community.

Societies come in many flavors.  No particular monetary system or
economy is associated with 'society'.

Socialism

1. a theory or system of social organization that advocates the vesting
of the ownership and control of the means of production and
distribution, of capital, land, etc., in the community as a whole.

2. procedure or practice in accordance with this theory.

3. (in Marxist theory) the stage following capitalism in the transition
of a society to communism, characterized by the imperfect implementation
of collectivist principles.

And so, we can see that socialism is the attempt to intertwine
the customs, traditions and values of a society with an
autocratic governing structure resulting in a sort of atheistic
theocracy.

Capitalism? Capitalism is not a social system nor is it a government.
It is a means and method of structuring a monetary and
banking system that relies on private capital and investment.

Capitalism is adaptable to various types of societies and governing
structures.

You're welcome.

