&gt; 1. a theory or system of social organization
&gt; that advocates the vesting of the ownership and
&gt; control of the means of production and
&gt; distribution, of capital, land, etc., in the
&gt; community as a whole. . . .

Ron Allen answers:
Please notice that socialism is about vesting
ownership and control of the means of production
and of distribution in the community as a whole.
In other words, capitalism is about vesting
ownership and control of the means of production,
etc., in a class within the community, a class of
proprietors, a minority class, a capitalist class.
In a socialist society, capital no longer has the
attribute of being private property, and so it is
usually said by socialists that capital as private
property ceases to exist.  In other words, capital
ceases to exist, because by definition capital is
private property.  What was capital under the rule
of capitalism will not longer have the peculiarity
of capital under capitalism.  When capital as
private property is socialized, capital as private
property ceases to exist.  Socialized capital is
not private capital, and so there are those who
prefer to say that capital no longer exists in a
socialist society.  Some do not see private
property as an essential property of capital, and
so they have no problem calling socialized and
democratized capital "capital".

There are other aspects of capital that are seen
as essential to the meaning of capital.  For
example, capital has the attribute of producing an
income for the proprietor.  As labor earns a wage,
so capital is seen to generate an income -- i.e.,
a profit, which is not an income earned by labor,
but an unearned income generated by ownership.
Another attribute of capital, under a capitalist
régime, is that capital employs labor; whereas
under a socialist system, labor employs capital.

The expression "community as a whole" points to
the democratic aspect of socialism.  In other
words, a socialist believes that democracy is
the socialization of the means of government, and
that a true democracy can only exist when both
industry and government are socialized and
democratized.  For the socialist, socialization
and democratization are equivalent expressions for
the same social relations.  Unless politics are
democratic, economics cannot be; and unless the
economy is democratic, politics cannot be truly
democratic.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
