Ron Allen answers:
Selfishness is not the only nature or attribute of
human beings.  We tend to be selfish for two basic
reasons.  The first reason for human selfishness
is material scarcity.  When there is scarcity, we
compete and we skirmish for what we need, or for
what we think we need.  The struggle to survive is
a dogfight.  The other reason for human greed and
selfishness is a combination of habit and of hope.
For so long now we have been contesting and
quarreling for scarce resources, and we have been
taught to hope for nothing better than scarcity.
The dominance of selfishness is not our first
nature; it is our second nature.  Our first
nature, our true nature, our human essence, is
both freedom and fellowship, both freedom and
friendship.  When we enjoy material abundance,
when we expect material abundance, then we have a
tendency to curtail selfishness and greed, and we
have a tendency to enlarge those graces, habits,
and manners which promote a more sociable and
amiable life.  When we can afford to be generous,
we tend to be less greedy.  When we can afford to
be more altruistic, we tend to be less avaricious.

