Ron Allen answers:
We already have a material solution to the problem
of material scarcity, thanks to capitalism's own
encouragement of industrial development and of
technological progress.  Of course, capitalism can
not, and will not solve the problem of material
scarcity, largely because scarcity is itself the
very backbone of profiteering capitalism.  In
other words, the material productive forces of
modern society already exist, thanks in part to
capitalism, but largely thanks to the unique human
ability to both see and solve problems.  However,
the existing capitalist relations of production
have become the fetters acting to curb the
material forces of production.  Capitalism creates
both prosperity and poverty.  It is because
capitalism has stimulated the creation of massive
industry and large-scale production that the very
existing of poverty has now become an artificial
hold over from previous times.  The solution has
been offered, and that solution to the capitalist
relations of production is called democratic-
socialism.  If we socialize and democratize the
material productive forces of modern technological
society, then we will have removed the capitalist
relations of production which have served both to
expand, and to retard the forces of production.
The profiteering capitalist class harnesses the
forces of production, managing these forces so as
to tame productivity in order to maximize profits.

If capitalism cannot solve the problem of scarcity
and poverty, then capitalism ought to be made to
move out of the way, and let socialism solve these
problems.  Capitalism solved the problem of
creating surplus wealth; but, capitalism has not
solved the problem of scarcity and poverty.  This
is why capitalism has always appeared hand in hand
both with extreme wealth and extreme want.  This
antipodal reality is an aspect of capitalism's
manifold and manifest contradictions.

